2000-2005 The OECD report effect on Panama¶

On 2000 the panama is black listed by the OECD as a fiscal paradise. The effect of this listing is immediate and we saw a decrease of the account. The same effect appears in 2002 when the Panama the 2002 OECD Model Agreement on Exchange of Information on Tax Matters is written and published. The investments rise after probably because entities has found a way to break this rules. In 2004, this report has been incorporated in the UN Model Tax Convention, an other decrease occurs.

top5_countries = countries[:5].index.tolist()
countries_year = evolution_feature_year[evolution_feature_year['n.countries'].isin(top5_countries)][['n.incorporation_date','n.countries','count']]
countries_year = countries_year.groupby(['n.incorporation_date','n.countries']).count().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
for country in top5_countries:
    data = countries_year[countries_year['n.countries']==country]
    data = data[data['n.incorporation_date']>=1975]

world_geo_path = './data/map.json'

with open(world_geo_path) as json_file:
    json_data = json.load(json_file)
countries_geo = pd.DataFrame(json_data) 
countries_geo['x'] = (countries_geo['north'].astype(float) + countries_geo['south'].astype(float)) /2
countries_geo['y'] = (countries_geo['east'].astype(float) + countries_geo['west'].astype(float)) /2
countries_geo = countries_geo[['country','x','y']]
countries_geo.set_index('country',inplace=True)

world_map = folium.Map([20,0], tiles='cartodbpositron', zoom_start=2)


entity_by_country = pd.DataFrame(panama_entity['n.countries'].value_counts())
entity_by_country.reset_index(inplace=True)
entity_by_country.columns = ['Country','count']
entity_by_country = entity_by_country[:30]

for i in range(0,len(entity_by_country)):
    country = entity_by_country.iloc[i]['Country']
    folium.CircleMarker(
      location=[countries_geo.ix[country]['x'], countries_geo.ix[country]['y']],
      popup=country+": "+str(entity_by_country.iloc[i]['count'])+" Entities",
      radius= entity_by_country.iloc[i]['count'].astype(float)/1000,
      color='blue',
      fill=True,
      fill_color='blue'
        
   ).add_to(world_map)

entity_address = registered_address[registered_address['node_1']<11000000]
dict_entity_address = entity_address[['node_1','node_2']].groupby('node_2')['node_1'].apply(lambda x: x.tolist()).to_dict()
famous_adress = sorted(dict_entity_address, key=lambda k: len(dict_entity_address[k]), reverse=True)
number_of_entities = list(map(len,list(map(dict_entity_address.get,famous_adress))))

Is there a correlation between the financial freedom and the number of entities coming from the same country in the dataset ?¶

To understand why entities are saving money in Panama, we gonna use this dataset: http://www.heritage.org/index. It contains differenct factors to determine how free a country is. We'll use the 2013 which is the oldest dataset on the webiste. It will represent the world status at this time before the leak. Our assumption here is that many accounts without date are recent accounts from the 2-4 previous year before the leak.
